  						<!--#beginContent#-->
  						<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='spti2' width='100%'>PLAYER STRATEGY - SHAMAN</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='dbti'>TRADE SKILLS AND THE BARBARIAN SHAMAN</font> - <small>Thurgrim, Rodcet Nife</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'>Shamans in Halas have many pitfalls to overcome-- a long distance to run/ swim to merchants, many multi-aggroing mobs, isolation from the
flourishing trade centers of Freeport, and a maze of peaks unlike any other starting area in all of Norrath. However, this environment can benefit a starting Shaman allowing him or her on the road to successful trade skills that will make a lot of money down the road.<br>
<br>
First, as a guideline, don't waste money on any trade gear until your Shaman has a good buff (Strengthen) and Burst of Flame. Burst of Flame is practically a
necessity and the buffs can make you invaluable to a low level group. So, assume from this point forward that this is taken care of and the Shaman in question has good spells.<br>
<br>
Now, the first trade skill to work on is Tailoring. Don't be shy about it, either. Invest skill points EARLY. A Shaman working right away on Tailoring can start making money from other newbies almost immediately in the form of trade. Leather armor for rusty spears and splintering clubs is a good deal and makes you quick friends who need the protection.<br>
<br>
Materials for tailoring are in plentiful supply in Everfrost as wolf and bear mobs respawn ad infinitum. However, saving for a sewing kit may be the biggest problem. Go for gnolls and goblins as soon as possible because they carry containers that go a long way in sale value toward purchasing that first small sewing kit. Once you have the kit you are on easy street. Pull wolves and bears every time you think you can take the mob. Use the kit as a container on the field (saving slots for other things) and buy patterns in bulk, carrying them with you as you go. This way you can convert a bulky ruined pelt to a light piece of armor immediately and begin offering trades to other newbs you happen across.<br>
<br>
Two problems arise with this system that are easily solved. First, the small sewing kit has only two slots. Simple, sell it and buy a large sewing kit
as soon as possible. It's an improved backpack in function as long as you do not hit the combine button. Second, your skill will max out for your level in no time with all the wolves and bears about. Don't worry, just keep tailoring, fighting, tailoring, ad nauseum. Soon you'll be making patchwork so fast you'll be able to fund your own suit of improved leather armor and nice mace or staff. Keep it up, don't quit, even if your skill peters out for a bit. You'll need that extra money down the road.<br>
<br>
Soon a Shaman is 5th level and the polar bear cubs and wolves stop being rewarding mobs. In addition it's about this time that tattered gear becomes trivial. No problem. Move onto the tundra's edge and begin pulling polar bears, snow leopards, and wooly spiders. Keep tailoring tattered for sale and trade and keep all spider silks. Silk is the next stage of development and can be quite an amazing money maker. Every time two spider silks are looted they should be woven into silk swatches (trivial a long time ago) and then sewn into armor. Not only does this keep a Shaman's skill rising but silk sells well to low level
spell casters. When you get a full pack of silk hop through Blackburrow and advertise silk armor for trade/ sale. Overnight you'll be making gold faster than you can tailor. Good, you'll need it at later levels when you branch out into
other trade skills.<br>
<br>
Once silk armor becomes easy you'll be pushing or passing the 7th level limit. Fear not, you have another trade skill to start early so when you move on in tailoring you'll be more than ready-- brewing! Roll up you sleeves and jump right in with only a little training (barring a high wisdom your successes will push this skill up quickly). If you are visiting the Qeynos Hills pick up snake scales and begin brewing bog juice. If not, don't worry, you can buy all the materials for short beer. Sell all your successes to buy more materials and get your brewing up to 25 or so (bog juice will only get to 21 so switch to short beer when it trivializes).<br>
<br>
That should give you two trade skills at a good ready level for life beyond 7th level. Keep making silk armor and save your high and medium quality pelts for later as your abilities allow you to travel to other trade centers safely.</p>

</body>

